ON THE 30th anniversary of the Tiananmen Square massacre, our correspondents recall a dark day and assess its legacy—not least the Communist Party's effort to suppress the memory of how it crushed China's pro-democracy movement. Could such widespread dissent flare up in today’s China? Also, why laws requiring immigrants to speak host-nations’ languages are counter-productive. Runtime: 22 min    Listen on: Apple Podcasts | Spotify | Google | Stitcher | TuneIn